// Problem
You are standing at the point 0 on a coordinate line. Your goal is to reach the point ğ‘›. In one minute, you can move by 2 or by 3 to the left or to the right (i.â€‰e., if your current coordinate is ğ‘¥, it can become ğ‘¥âˆ’3, ğ‘¥âˆ’2, ğ‘¥+2 or ğ‘¥+3). Note that the new coordinate can become negative.

Your task is to find the minimum number of minutes required to get from the point 0 to the point ğ‘›.

You have to answer ğ‘¡ independent test cases.

//Input
The first line of the input contains one integer ğ‘¡ (1â‰¤ğ‘¡â‰¤10^4) â€” the number of test cases. Then ğ‘¡ lines describing the test cases follow.

The ğ‘–-th of these lines contains one integer ğ‘› (1â‰¤ğ‘›â‰¤10^9) â€” the goal of the ğ‘–-th test case.

// Output

For each test case, print one integer â€” the minimum number of minutes required to get from the point 0
to the point ğ‘› for the corresponding test case.

// Example
// Input
4
1
3
4
12

// Output
2
1
2
4

// Solution
#include <bits/stdc++.h>

using namespace std;

int main() {
  int t;
  cin >> t;
  while (t--) {
    int n;
    cin >> n;
    if (n == 1) {
      cout << 2 << endl;
      continue;
    }
    cout << (int)ceil(n/3.0) << endl;
  }
  return 0;
}
